As recommended by the Food and Drug Administration
(FDA), all samples with positive or equivocal
results in a Borrelia burgdorferi antibody screen
will be tested using a blot method. Positive or
equivocal screening test results should not be
interpreted as truly positive until verified as such
using a supplemental assay (e.g., B. burgdorferi blot).

antibodies may be falsely negative in early stages
of Lyme disease, including the period when erythema
migrans is apparent.

This is a 43-year-old male, non-smoker, referred by Lucy Fratto with a significant medical history of depression and mood disorder for which he follows with his psychiatrist, Dr. Al-Tariq, who presents today for initial CV consultation after a recent hospitalization for TIA. He is a heavy equipment operator for union. He has 2 healthy children and lives in Mount Hope. His PCP is Dr. Hirsch who he has yet to establish care with. He follows with psychiatry, Dr. Al-Tariq. He has a family history of his dad passing in his 60s but he is unsure of the cause and his mother is alive and healthy. He has a past surgical history of surgical intervention of his knee 9 years ago and rhinoplasty after fracture. His only medications include aspirin, Lamictal and Prozac at this time. He was hospitalized approximately 1 week ago after having an episode while in Seaside, New Jersey were he had an episode of epigastric chest pain which he initially believed was heartburn. He reports that it worsened and developed into severe chest pain and had difficulty breathing. He reports that his face and his arm went numb.
